<DOC><DOCNO> AP890603-0033 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-89 0517EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-RefugeeStandoff     06-03 0226</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Refugee Standoff,0234</SECOND><HEAD>Immigration Officials Question Haitian Refugees</HEAD><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Haitian refugees threatened to throw babiesoverboard during an eight-hour standoff at sea before agreeing toboard Coast Guard cutters, officials said.   Immigration and Naturalization Service agents Friday wereinterviewing 109 Haitians after flying to the scene about 100 milessouth of Miami, said Lt. Jeff Karonis, a Coast Guard spokesman.   Karonis said the refugees brandished knives and machetes whentheir 50-foot wooden sailboat was intercepted Thursday by the CoastGuard.   The refugees refused to let the Coast Guard board their boat,Karonis said, and the group's leader threatened to throw fivebabies overboard.   The Coast Guard cutters Shearwater and Matagorda were sent outto help a third cutter, the Metompkin, which made the interception.   During the standoff, the INS agents and an interpreter wereairlifted to the scene.   Late Thursday, after hours of negotiations, INS and Coast Guardofficials managed ``to convince the Haitians to go peacefully'' tothe cutters, Karonis said.   No one was injured, and a small Coast Guard launch crew rescueda woman who jumped overboard during the standoff.   Two of the Haitians were airlifted from the scene to Miami'sJackson Memorial Hospital. One was suffering from hypothermia,Karonis said, and the other appeared to have suffered a seizure.   The hospital on Friday refused to release details of theircondition.</TEXT></DOC>